          <h1>What to Expect During Your First Month on GLP-1 Medication</h1>
        </div>
        <div class="article-body">
          <aside class="tldr-box" aria-label="Article summary">
            <span class="tldr-label">TL;DR</span>
            <p class="tldr-summary">Your first month on GLP-1 medication is an adjustment period. Patients start at the lowest dose (semaglutide 0.25 mg or tirzepatide 2.5 mg), gradually notice appetite reduction over weeks 1–3, and typically lose 3–6 pounds by week 4. Most side effects are mild, GI-related, and improve with time. Communication with your physician and basic lifestyle habits (hydration, protein, movement) drive success.</p>
            <ul class="tldr-points">
              <li><strong>Week 1:</strong> lowest starting dose; subtle appetite changes; mild nausea possible.</li>
              <li><strong>Week 2:</strong> side effects often peak as medication stabilizes; cravings begin to decrease.</li>
              <li><strong>Week 3:</strong> meaningful hunger reduction for most patients; good time to establish healthy eating patterns.</li>
              <li><strong>Week 4:</strong> first physician check-in; typical weight loss 3–6 lbs; dose may be increased.</li>
              <li><strong>Managing side effects:</strong> small frequent meals, 64+ oz water daily, 60–80 g protein, rotate injection sites.</li>
              <li><strong>Expectation:</strong> GLP-1 treatment is a marathon — greatest results typically between months 3–12.</li>
            </ul>
          </aside>
          <p>Starting a GLP-1 medication is a significant step in your weight loss journey. Knowing what to expect during your first four weeks can help you feel prepared, manage side effects effectively, and stay motivated as the medication begins to take effect. Here is a detailed week-by-week guide based on common patient experiences and clinical data.</p>

          <h3>Week 1: Getting Started</h3>
          <div class="week-card">
            <h4><i class="fas fa-syringe"></i> Your First Injection</h4>
            <p>Your first week begins with the lowest dose. For semaglutide, this is typically 0.25 mg; for tirzepatide, it starts at 2.5 mg. These low starting doses are designed to let your body adjust gradually. Your LDRGLPRx care team will provide detailed injection instructions and answer any questions before you begin.</p>
            <p>During the first few days, you may begin to notice <strong>subtle changes in appetite</strong>. Some patients report feeling less interest in food or feeling satisfied more quickly during meals. Others notice minimal changes at this early stage, and that is perfectly normal. The medication is building up in your system and effects increase over time.</p>
            <p><strong>Common experiences:</strong> Mild nausea (usually temporary), slight decrease in appetite, occasional fatigue as your body adjusts. Some patients experience no side effects at all during week one.</p>
          </div>

          <h3>Week 2: Adjusting to the Medication</h3>
          <div class="week-card">
            <h4><i class="fas fa-chart-line"></i> Changes Begin</h4>
            <p>By week two, you take your second injection at the same starting dose. Many patients start to notice more consistent changes in hunger patterns. You may find that you think about food less frequently, experience reduced cravings (especially for sugary or high-calorie foods), and feel satisfied after eating smaller portions than usual.</p>
            <p>Gastrointestinal side effects, if present, may be most noticeable around this time as the medication levels stabilize. <strong>Nausea is the most commonly reported side effect</strong>, occurring in approximately 40-45% of patients at some point during treatment. It is usually mild to moderate and improves significantly over the following weeks.</p>
            <p><strong>Weight changes:</strong> Some patients see initial weight movement of 1-3 pounds during the first two weeks. However, do not be discouraged if the scale has not moved yet. The medication needs time to reach therapeutic levels.</p>
          </div>

          <h3>Week 3: Building Momentum</h3>
          <div class="week-card">
            <h4><i class="fas fa-utensils"></i> New Eating Patterns Emerge</h4>
            <p>By week three, most patients report a meaningful reduction in hunger and appetite. You may find that portions that previously seemed normal now feel too large. Many patients describe this as a fundamental shift in their relationship with food -- the constant background noise of hunger and cravings begins to quiet down.</p>
            <p>This is an excellent time to focus on establishing healthy eating patterns that will support long-term success. Because you naturally want to eat less, you can be more intentional about choosing nutrient-dense foods. Focus on lean proteins, vegetables, fruits, and whole grains. Your LDRGLPRx medical team can provide personalized nutrition guidance.</p>
            <p><strong>Energy levels:</strong> Some patients notice improved energy as they begin eating cleaner and their blood sugar levels stabilize. Others may still experience mild fatigue. Both responses are normal.</p>
          </div>

          <h3>Week 4: Finding Your Rhythm</h3>
          <div class="week-card">
            <h4><i class="fas fa-scale-balanced"></i> Early Results and Next Steps</h4>
            <p>At the four-week mark, you will typically have your first check-in with your LDRGLPRx physician. By this point, most patients have lost between <strong>3-6 pounds</strong>, though individual results vary. Some patients lose more, particularly those starting at higher body weights, while others may see more gradual progress that accelerates with dose increases.</p>
            <p>Your physician will evaluate your response to the medication, review any side effects, and determine whether to increase your dose. The dose-escalation schedule is typically every four weeks, and higher doses generally produce greater appetite suppression and weight loss. Your prescriber will adjust the pace based on your tolerance and response.</p>
          </div>

          <h3>Managing Common Side Effects</h3>
          <p>Understanding how to manage side effects can make a significant difference in your treatment experience. Here are practical strategies for the most common issues:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Nausea:</strong> Eat smaller, more frequent meals. Avoid lying down immediately after eating. Bland, low-fat foods tend to be better tolerated. Ginger tea or ginger supplements may help.</li>
            <li><strong>Constipation:</strong> Increase water intake to at least 64 ounces daily. Add fiber-rich foods gradually. Gentle physical activity like walking can help stimulate digestion.</li>
            <li><strong>Fatigue:</strong> Ensure adequate sleep, stay hydrated, and eat enough protein. Fatigue typically resolves within the first few weeks.</li>
            <li><strong>Injection site reactions:</strong> Rotate injection sites between your abdomen, thigh, and upper arm. Minor redness or swelling at the injection site is common and usually resolves quickly.</li>
            <li><strong>Decreased appetite:</strong> While reduced appetite is the goal, make sure you are still eating enough to meet basic nutritional needs. Aim for a minimum of 1,200 calories for women and 1,500 for men unless otherwise directed by your physician.</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Tips for a Successful First Month</h3>
          <ol>
            <li><strong>Stay hydrated.</strong> Drink at least 64 ounces of water daily. Dehydration worsens nausea and constipation.</li>
            <li><strong>Prioritize protein.</strong> Aim for 60-80 grams of protein per day to preserve muscle mass during weight loss.</li>
            <li><strong>Move your body.</strong> Start with 20-30 minutes of walking most days. Exercise enhances the medication's effects and supports metabolic health.</li>
            <li><strong>Track your progress.</strong> Keep a simple journal noting your weight, meals, energy levels, and any side effects. This information helps your physician fine-tune your treatment.</li>
            <li><strong>Be patient.</strong> GLP-1 medications are a marathon, not a sprint. The most significant results typically occur between months 3 and 12 of treatment.</li>
            <li><strong>Communicate with your care team.</strong> Report any concerning symptoms promptly. Your LDRGLPRx physician is there to support you and can adjust your treatment plan as needed.</li>
          </ol>

          <div class="tip-box">
            <strong><i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i> Key Takeaway:</strong> Your first month on GLP-1 medication is about adjustment and establishing a foundation. Side effects are common but manageable, and most improve significantly over time. Stay in close communication with your medical team for the best results.
          </div>
        </div>
